# Networking Devices — Switches, Firewalls, IDS/IPS

**Date:** January 6,2026.


## Switch

Switches are smarter than hubs. Instead of broadcasting everything to
everyone, a switch learns which device lives on which port using MAC
addresses and only sends traffic where it actually needs to go.

They operate at Layer 2 of OSI — the Data Link layer. MAC addresses,
frames, thats the world a switch lives in.

Most switches run on dedicated hardware chips called ASICs (Application
Specific Integrated Circuits). This is why switching is so fast —
its not running software decisions, its hardware-level.

One thing i didnt know before — enterprise switches often support
**PoE (Power over Ethernet)**. Meaning they can deliver electrical power
through the network cable itself. Thats how IP cameras and access points
get powered without a separate power cable.

**Pentesting angle:** Switches arent passive. VLAN hopping, MAC flooding,
and ARP spoofing all target switch behaviour. MAC flooding overwhelms
the MAC address table forcing the switch to behave like a hub — suddenly
youre seeing traffic you shouldnt.


## Firewall

Basic job: filter traffic based on TCP/UDP port numbers and IP addresses.
Old firewalls were simple packet filters — does this port match a rule?
Allow or deny.

Modern firewalls do a lot more:

- **Application awareness** — they can identify what application is
  generating traffic, not just what port its using. An attacker running
  a C2 over port 443 might fool a basic firewall but not an
  application-aware one.

- **VPN termination** — most enterprise firewalls handle VPN connections,
  encrypting traffic between sites or remote users.

- **NAT (Network Address Translation)** — translates private internal IPs
  to a public IP. This is why your whole house shares one public IP address.

- **Dynamic routing** — some firewalls can also act as Layer 3 switches
  and handle routing between subnets.


## IDS and IPS — the hacker point from my notes

This is where it gets interesting from an attacker perspective.

**IDS (Intrusion Detection System)** — monitors traffic and raises an
alarm when it sees something suspicious. Detects, doesnt stop.

**IPS (Intrusion Prevention System)** — actually blocks the traffic inline.
Stops it before it reaches the target.

The distinction matters when you're planning an attack. An IDS means
someone might notice you. An IPS means you might get blocked mid-exploitation.

What they look for:
- Known exploit signatures (buffer overflows, shellcode patterns)
- Cross-site scripting patterns
- Anomalous behaviour that doesnt match a signature but looks weird

The weakness of both is that they rely heavily on known signatures.
Novel exploits, obfuscated payloads, and slow/low attacks can slip through.
Thats why evasion is its own skill in pentesting.


